# Medial Epicondyle

> The **medial epicondyle** is the prominent bony projection on the medial side of the distal [[Humerus]], serving as the common origin of the flexor-pronator muscle group and the site where the **ulnar nerve** passes in the cubital tunnel.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Humerus]] — distal medial humerus
- [[Ulnar Nerve]] — passes in the cubital tunnel posterior to the medial epicondyle
- Flexor-pronator group — common flexor origin (FCR, PL, FCU, FDS, pronator teres)
- [[Medial Collateral Ligament]] — UCL originates from medial epicondyle

## 🗂️ Key Facts
| Property | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| Location | Medial distal humerus (easily palpable) |
| Nerve relation | Ulnar nerve runs in cubital tunnel directly posterior |
| Common origin | Flexor-pronator muscles of the forearm |
| "Funny bone" | Striking the cubital tunnel → ulnar nerve tingling in ring + little finger |

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Medial epicondylitis (golfer's elbow)** — Overuse tendinopathy at the common flexor origin; medial elbow pain
- **Ulnar nerve entrapment (cubital tunnel syndrome)** — Tingling in ring and little fingers; numbness at medial epicondyle
- **Medial epicondyle avulsion fracture** — Common in adolescents; can trap ulnar nerve
- **UCL injury (Tommy John)** — UCL originates here; rupture in overhead throwing athletes

